> On Thu, Nov 1, 2012 at 11:25 PM, Nancy Thalia Reynolds <
> ntreynolds@comcast.net> wrote:
> 
>> 
>> 
>> I apologize for how vague these suggestions are. I've had to place most of
>> my books and files in storage for a couple of years, so I don't have
>> physical access to them. Hence I often can't cite specifics, but maybe the
>> titles will jog someone's better memory or library. I'll begin with those
>> I'm sure of:
>> 
>> In Noel Streatfeild's BALLET SHOES, the three sisters are taken on a walk
>> to see the dollhouses at the Victoria & Albert Museum most days.
>> 
>> In American Jean Davies Okimoto's THE ECLIPSE OF MOONBEAM DAWSON, a
>> pivotal scene takes place in a museum (either UBC's Museum of Anthropology
>> or the Royal British Columbia Museum) involving artworks by the great Haida
>> artist Bill Reid.
>> 
>> In Edward Eager's THE TIME GARDEN, don't the children visit Orchard House,
>> once the Alcott family home, now a museum, in Concord, MA?
>> 
>> Australian Cassandra Gold's THE MUSEUM OF MARY CHILD features a created
>> museum.
>> 
>> THE EDIBLE WOMAN, Margaret Atwood's first novel, which I would
>> characterize as crossover YA, set in Toronto, has a memorable scene inside
>> the Royal Ontario Museum's ancient Egyptian room.
>> 
>> And works by other Canadian writers: I believe there's a museum in Welwyn
>> Wilton Katz's FALSE FACE.
>> 
>> I have a feeling museums play a role in woks by Kit Pearson (AWAKE AND
>> DREAMING? or the Guests of War trilogy?).
>> 
>> Nancy Thalia Reynolds
>> MIXED HERITAGE IN YOUNG ADULT LITERATURE (Scarecrow Press, 2009)
